# ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

## Key Breaking Changes

1. **`Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(..., true)`** — These relied on `Thread.Abort`, which **does not exist** in .NET Core. No `ThreadAbortException` is ever thrown.
2. **`Response.Write()`** — Replaced by returning `IActionResult` types.
3. **`Response.Clear()` / `AddHeader()`** — No longer needed; the response pipeline handles this.
4. **Web Forms event handlers** (`btnExport_Click`) — Don't exist in MVC/Core. Use action methods.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // btnExport_Click → action method returning FileResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // File() sets Content-Type, Content-Disposition, and writes the body.
        // No Response.Clear/End needed — the framework handles the full response.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // btnRedirect_Click → action method returning IActionResult
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // RedirectResult does NOT abort the thread — code after this
            // WILL execute unless you return immediately.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ⚠️ DO NOT catch ThreadAbortException — it will never be thrown.
        // Keeping that catch block is dead code and masks intent.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Code runs after redirect** | In Framework, `Response.Redirect(url, true)` aborted the thread so nothing after it executed. In Core, `Redirect()` just returns an object — **you must `return` it** or subsequent code runs silently. |
| **Swallowing `ThreadAbortException`** | A common Framework pattern. In Core this catch block is dead code. Remove it — if left in, it may mask real bugs if someone later changes the exception hierarchy. |
| **`Response.End()` doesn't exist** | Any code that relied on `Response.End()` to short-circuit must be restructured to `return` an `IActionResult`. |
| **Null-ref on `User.Identity`** | `User.Identity` can be `null` in Core if no auth middleware is configured. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the `[Authorize]` attribute. |
| **Auth via attribute** | Prefer `[Authorize]` over manual checks — it hooks into the middleware pipeline and returns proper 401/403 responses. |

## Better Pattern with `[Authorize]`

```csharp
[Authorize] // Returns 401 automatically — no manual check needed
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
{
    try
    {
        ProcessRequest();
        return Redirect("/success");
    }
    catch (Exception ex)
    {
        LogError(ex);
        return Redirect("/error");
    }
}
```

Configure the auth redirect in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */)
    .AddCookie(options =>
    {
        options.LoginPath = "/login";  // replaces manual redirect
    });
```

**TL;DR**: The core mental model shift is that ASP.NET Core actions **return results** instead of **mutating a shared `Response` object and aborting the thread**. Every `Response.Redirect` / `Response.End` / `Response.Write` becomes a `return SomeActionResult()`.
